#Text=Diving in Guam
#Text=This article is intended to provide the already qualified Scuba diver with information which will help to plan dives in the waters of Guam , whether as a local resident or a visitor .
#Text=Information is provided without prejudice , and is not guaranteed accurate or complete .
#Text=Use it at your own risk .
#Text=Understand
#Text=Guam
#Text=has some of the best dive sites in the world since there has been minimal tourist impact compared to other better known dive locations .
#Text=Piti Bomb Holes

#Text=has been built up as a tourist attraction allowing tourists to descend into an observatory where they can take in the beauty that has grown in a sinkhole . ( The name " Bomb Holes " is a misnomer . ) Divers may dive around this attraction and feed shoals of fish for the amusement of the tourists inside the subaquatic observatory as much as for the divers ' own amusement .
#Text=While many of the dive sites can be reached by land , some of these entry points require a long walk over coral or a long surface swim .
#Text=Also , because so much of the island is controlled by U.S. military bases , many of the dive sites are accessed by land through the military bases .
#Text=Dive sites
#Text=The list below are some of the dive sites in Guam .
#Text=North of Piti Bomb Holes
#Text=Gun Beach
#Text=Gun Beach is the only Scuba dive site in Tumon Bay , the main resort hotel-tourism area .
#Text=Most other sites , are about a 30-minute drive from the Tumon hotel district .
#Text=This dive site is at the extreme North side of Tumon Bay , past the last hotel , and down a short dirt road which has a sign warning that the road is closed to the public .
#Text=There are no facilities at the site , although it is within a 5-minute walk of the nearest hotel .

#Text=Note that there is NO protected area of the shallows which are sufficiently deep to conduct the shallow-water dive lesson commonly given in " resort diving " , although the site is nearly attractive in other respects .
#Text=This beach dive is started and ended by walking in ankle-to-knee-deep water perpendicular to the beach , along a thigh-width pipe .
#Text=At the wave-break zone , this pipe is at the bottom of a rip-current notch in the reef .
#Text=The pipe has rough joints at intervals of about one yard , making it almost a perfect " ladder " to easily work back in toward shore against that outgoing rip-current .
#Text=Once past the wave-break zone , the reef slopes off at a gentle 20-degree angle toward deep water .
#Text=The shallowest portions almost reach the water 's surface , while the deep end finishes in a sandy plain roughly 90 ' – 100 feet down .

#Text=Divers should confine their attention to the side of the dive site closest to the center of Tumon Bay rather than " away " , because the " away " side is generally populated with dead corals and Crown of Thorns starfish .
#Text=The " near " side , on the other hand , has excellent corals : candlesticks , brain corals , and antler corals .
#Text=There are hand-shaped " spider " shells , an abundance of fish life , and an offshore permanent boat mooring .
#Text=Warning .
#Text=This dive site has a risk of strong outflowing currents during falling tides so divers must take care to return with ample air in order to hug the bottom .
#Text=The knuckled joints of the cable pipes are helpful in order to return against this strong tide , but only if the diver has enough air to get to them .
#Text=It is best to study the tides and plan for an incoming tide at time of return until the diver becomes familiar with diving this location .
#Text=It is recommended that interested divers join the local shore dive group at MDA or hire local guides .
#Text=Napoleon Cut
#Text=Northern Caves
#Text=Shark 's Hole
#Text=The Pinnacle
#Text=Asan Cut
#Text=Blue and White
#Text=Dolphin Point
#Text=Double Reef
#Text=Piti Channel
#Text=South of Piti Bomb Holes / Apra Harbor
#Text=Fish Eye
#Text=This walk-in site has more than 200 fish species as it is a marine park and breeding site for fish and invertebrates .
#Text=Divers can see the healthy reef on the south side of the observatory , feed the fish and even snorkel around the observatory itself .
#Text=A visit to the unique observatory fun for the non diving family members who can see you at a 20-foot depth .
#Text=American Tanker
#Text=The " American Tanker " is actually a large 300+ ft concrete barge .
#Text=Recent information found on the internet indicates that in late 1944 the barges were loaded in Honolulu with war supplies , and then towed to Guam from Honolulu by the USS Bannock and Arikara .
#Text=Later they were put into position on the Calahan bank by the USS Gear and sunk to provide a breakwater at the mouth of Apra Harbor .
#Text=American Tanker pilothouse is at a depth of 40 feet/13 meters .
#Text=Depth to the main deck is 60/20 meters and the ship has a list to the right ( starboard side ) .
#Text=Family Beach
#Text=Family Beach , located near Outhouse Beach , is within Apra Harbor , thereby guaranteeing that during most weather it is divable .
#Text=Unlike Outhouse Beach , it is fairly brightly lit , with moderately well developed corals and moderately abundant sea life .
#Text=Parking is alongside a white sandy beach .
#Text=From there , divers wade out on a flat , sandy/grassy bottom in knee-to-waist-high water until reaching a narrow ( 30 ' wide ) canyon that runs parallel to the beach .
#Text=Diving is typically done along near and far walls of the canyon , in 6 ' – 30 ' of water .
#Text=Care should be taken not to stir up the sandy-silty bottom of the canyon , in order to maintain good visibility during the dive .

#Text=The primary reason that Outhouse Beach is a common dive site , while Family Beach is not , is that Family Beach 's access is controlled by a private owner who may charge fees or deny access , whereas Outhouse Beach is not hampered in this way .
#Text=Finger Reef
#Text=Like Outhouse Beach and Family Beach , Finger Reef is inside Apra Harbor , and therefore divable even when rough weather threatens to make most of Guam 's divesites undivable .
#Text=There , the similarity ends .
#Text=Finger Reef is an extremely well developed reef wall along the opposite side of Apra Harbor , much closer to the Harbor 's sea access opening .
#Text=It is quite far from shore , and the nearby shore is part of a restricted-access military base , so almost all divers reach the site by diveboat .
#Text=The reef starts at roughly 20~30 ' and drops off to roughly 60 ' .
#Text=Dives are typically done as wall-dives , but not drift dives .
#Text=Divers typically make their ascent and descent along the boat 's anchor rope , and the boat is motionless during the dive .
#Text=Because Finger Reef is full of sealife , protected by the harbor , relatively shallow , and near Blue Hole , it is a very popular second dive of the day after visiting Blue Hole .
#Text=Gab Gab
#Text=Located in Naval Station on the western coast of Guam , Gab Gab Beach is in a restricted naval base so only military personnel will have access to Gab Gab Beach .
#Text=The beach is great for snorkelers , and beginning and experienced divers .
#Text=Divers can do a beach entry or come in off a boat .
#Text=There are coral slopes and plenty of fish .
#Text=Gab Gab 2
#Text=Accessible as a shore dive past Gab Gab if you 're in the military , short boat ride otherwise .
#Text=Dive site is marked with a white buoy directly across from " Gab Gab " beach on ComNavMar Naval Base .
#Text=Fish feeding areas are set up to get large amounts of fish to gather as scenery for a small tourist submarine ( " Atlantis " ) which makes trips through the area .
#Text=Large amount of fish , a few lionfish and a rather large eel that hangs out by the feed bucket .
#Text=Be careful around the Giant Trevally Jacks as they are known to bite fingers .
#Text=Outhouse Beach
#Text=Outhouse Beach is a popular site for scuba certification dives .
#Text=On a typical day , five to ten scuba schools ' vans will be gathered at this site conducting Open Water certification dives .
#Text=This should not , however , be taken as a sign that the site is exceptionally pretty .
#Text=In fact , it is not .
#Text=The steep beach is made of large pebbles .
#Text=Underwater , there is little or no reef , and little sea life .
#Text=Horizontal visibility underwater is between 10 and 20 yards .
#Text=The main reason for its popularity with dive shops is that the site is within Apra harbor , virtually guaranteeing that even during inclement weather the site will be divable .
#Text=In addition , the beach entry is particularly easy , with no sharp corals to walk over nor long surface swim .
#Text=Family beach is at the end of the road past Outhouse Beach and a dive flag is required there .
#Text=Kitsugawa Maru
#Text=To the west of the Tokai Maru lies a third huge shipwreck , the Japanese freighter Kitsugawa Maru - another casualty of the days prior to the US invasion of Guam in 1944 .

#Text=Torpedoed by the submarine USS Seahorse , she was towed into the harbor for repairs and , while at anchor , was attacked by bombs and rocket fire from raiding US aircraft , finally sinking when her engine
#Text=room exploded , tearing the ship in two and sending her into the depths where she sits upright on her keel at an average depth of 140 feet .
#Text=SMS Cormoran
#Text=The 290-foot Cormoran lies in 120 feet of water on her right ( starboard ) side directly beside the Tokai Maru ( which went down in 1943 ) .

#Text=The easiest way to reach the Cormoran ( and dive on two ship from two different wars at the same time ) is to follow the midsection hull of the Tokai over the side until you see the Cormoran at 80 feet .
#Text=The hull of the Cormoran is intact .
#Text=The engine room is easily accessible through the skylights , and most of the superstructure is relatively intact .
#Text=Visibility averages 35 – 40 ' , but can vary due to the tide and large ship traffic in the harbor .
#Text=An average diving depth to see all of the port side would be 80-100 feet .
#Text=Visibility averages 35-40 ' , but can vary due weather and tidal flow in the harbor .
#Text=Tokai Maru
#Text=The Tokai Maru is a large ship , over 440 feet long .
#Text=She rests in 120 feet with an 85 degree list to port ( left ) .
#Text=The shallowest part of the ship is the upper forward bridge area at a depth of 40 feet .
#Text=A torpedo has blown a hole in the port
#Text=#3 cargo hold , and this is undoubtedly the torpedo that sunk her .
#Text=There is damage on the starboard bow , but this is believed to have been inflicted on the first attack in January 1943 .
#Text=The cargo holds contains remains of truck frames , beds , scrap steel , and miscellaneous objects .
#Text=The engine room is huge , and both of her engines , catwalks , and panels are intact .
#Text=The after-deck house in the stern of the vessel contains at least four unexploded depth charges , which are plainly visible from the top of the structure .
#Text=DO NOT attempt to touch or move these depth charges .
#Text=Visibility averages 35-40 feet , but can vary due to the tide and large ship traffic in the harbor .
#Text=A good average diving depth to see all of the Tokai would be 60-80 feet .
#Text=Blue Hole
#Text=The
#Text=" Blue Hole " is within 30 yards of shore .
#Text=However , the shore it 's near is a towering , jagged cliff on a military base .
#Text=Therefore , it is typically accessed by divers via boat .
#Text=The Blue Hole is , like Saies Tunnel in Palau , a wide tunnel from shallow to deep points within a submerged wall .
#Text=The hole 's shallowest point is within a few yards of the edge of an extreme vertical dropoff , and lies in about 40 ' of water .
#Text=The tunnel below it is a straight vertical plunge to the extreme limit of recreational diving depths , roughly 110 feet ( depending on the tides ) .
#Text=The tunnel is roughly as wide as a passenger van .
#Text=There is a permanent boat mooring at the top of the tunnel , and descent is usually made along this anchor rope .
#Text=The dive site is not particularly well endowed with corals .
#Text=For a good coral reef , boats typically make a second , shallower dive at nearby Hap 's Reef ( outside Apra Harbor ) or Finger Reef ( inside Apra Harbor ) .
#Text=Horizontal visibility is typically 20 to 30 yards or better .

#Text=Caution should be taken regarding depth and nitrogen accumulation , since the extreme water clarity and extreme depths along the wall can easily cause unprepared divers to dive deeper than they 'd intended .
#Text=Hap 's Reef
#Text=Hap 's Reef is a well-developed coral mound several hundred yards offshore , in roughly 30 ' – 40 ' of water , with flat terrain and shallow sandy valleys surrounding it .
#Text=It is generally accessed by boat , and is a favorite ' second dive of the day " after diving the nearby Blue Hole .
